fields.name: 2nd Placement Day "Saturday Music" - New Supplemental Music Program
fields.description:
The Pittsburgh Public Schools and River City Brass have teamed up to provide “Saturday Music,” a new free supplemental program designed to explore and grow the musical interests and abilities of Pittsburgh Public Schools students.  The program will offer the following five ensembles for students in grades 5-12: Bridge Band (grades 5-8), Youth Brass Band (grades 9-12), String Ensembles (grades 5-12), and Gospel Choirs (grades 5-12).   

“Saturday Music” will meet Saturday mornings from 9AM-12PM, beginning with Placement Day on January 7 - May 12, 2012. Students should arrive to Placement Day with their instrument, piece of music, and completed placement form, which can be found online at www.pps.k12.pa.us.  Placement Day is not an audition.  Students will be placed in the appropriate ensemble based on skill level. Please call (412) 758-5842 or (412) 434-7222 X 293 with any quetions.

fields.name: Diabolique
fields.description: Before Psycho, Peeping Tom, and Repulsion, there was Diabolique. Phipps and the Green Building Alliance (GBA) are proud to present two special events at the Conservatory with renowned green building expert Jason McLennan on February 27, 2012: A Lunch and Learn from 11:30 a.m.-1 p.m., and Drinks and Conservation from 5:30-8 p.m. 

One of the most influential players in the movement, McLennan has had a major impact on the direction of green building in the U.S. and Canada. Among his many accolades, he is founder of the Living Building Challenge (an international green building program through which Phipps is seeking certification for the Center for Sustainable Landscapes); CEO of the Cascadia Green Building Council (the Pacific Northwest's leading organization in the field of green building and sustainable development); and co-creator of Pharos, the most advanced building material rating system in North America. 

McLennan's Lunch and Learn presentation will focus on the topic of community regeneration and living buildings, while the Drinks and Conversation talk will cover the Living Building Challenge and more.

fields.name: Orchid and Tropical Bonsai Show
fields.description:
Please join us for the Orchid and Tropical Bonsai Show, highlighting some of the most spectacular and precious specimens in our extensive collections. As our guest, you are invited to take a relaxing stroll through the gardens, gather practical orchid growing tips, discover more about bonsai styles, and simply delight in the beauty of our natural wonders.

The World of Orchids
Incredibly varied and colorful, orchids come in all hues, shapes and sizes, providing a feast for the eyes with their delicacy, detail and splendor. From the popular Phalaenopsis with their moth and butterfly-like flowers to the enchanting Paphiopedilums with their slipper-like pouches, we will showcase the four main families, sharing their unique characteristics.   

The Art of Bonsai
The ancient Japanese art form known as bonsai features miniature, potted trees cultivated to imitate the growth habits of their mature counterparts in nature. Classified by size and style based on the shape of their trunks and branches, bonsai take many forms – from the iconic formal upright bonsai to the more dramatic slant bonsai that resemble windswept trees.

The Orchid and Tropical Bonsai Show, which runs from Jan. 14-March 4, 2012, will be open daily from 9:30 a.m. to 5 p.m. and until 10 p.m. on Fridays. Admission costs $12 for adults, $11 for seniors (age 62 and older) and students (with valid ID), and $9 for children (ages 2-18). Members and children under 2 enter for free.

fields.description:
Join us for a concert featuring the two-time GRAMMY® winning Turtle Island Quartet with mandolinist Mike Marshall, one of the most accomplished and versatile acoustic musicians performing today. They will perform "Solstice Celebration", a concert showcasing the music associated with what is referred to in both the Jewish and Hindu traditions as the Festival Of Lights.

From the songs of Chanukah, to the music of India’s Diwali, to the old English carols and Scottish reels of the 16th century, Mike Marshall and TIQ explore the timeless music that has been an integral part of winter holiday celebrations for centuries. The program also features music from Vince Guaraldi’s beloved A Charlie Brown Christmas, as well as revisiting famous classical gems that have become so indelibly tied to the holiday season.
